data.chText: 无力的；无生气的；无精神的
他的手一软，刀子当啷一声掉到地上。
data.enText: His hand went limp and the knife clattered to the ground.

data.chText: 她感到浑身无力，累极了。
这帽子软得不成样子了。
data.enText: The hat had become limp and shapeless.

data.chText: 她的头发蓬松地垂在前额上。
data.enText: Her hair hung limply over her forehead.
to walk slowly or with difficulty because one leg is injured

data.chText: 她把脚踝扭伤了，一瘸一拐地走着。
data.enText: She had twisted her ankle and was limping.

data.chText: 马特忍着痛歪歪斜斜地走出了运动场。
data.enText: Matt limped painfully off the field.

data.chText: （受损后）缓慢行进，艰难地移动
data.enText: to move slowly or with difficulty after being damaged

data.chText: 飞机艰难地返回了机场。
data.enText: The plane limped back to the airport.

data.chText: 政府按老一套挣扎着应付。
data.enText: The government was limping along in its usual way.
a way of walking in which one leg is used less than normal because it is injured or stiff

data.chText: 有点 / 明显地一瘸一拐地走
data.enText: to walk with a slight/pronounced limp

simple_means.memory_skill: lim 门槛，引申为“限制” + p → 走路受限制的 → 跛行

means: (受损后)缓慢行进，艰难地移动

tr: the uneven manner of walking that results from an injured leg
walk impeded by some physical limitation or injury
example: The old woman hobbles down to the store every day
the boat limped into the harbor

tr: lacking in strength or firmness or resilience
example: a limp gesture as if waving away all desire to know" G.K.Chesterto

value.def: If a person or animal limps, they walk with difficulty or in an uneven way because one of their legs or feet is hurt.

example.ex: I wasn't badly hurt, but I injured my thigh and had to limp...
example.tran: 我伤得不重，但一条大腿伤到了，只好一瘸一拐地走。

example.ex: He had to limp off with a leg injury.
example.tran: 他腿上有伤，离开时只能一瘸一拐地走。

example.ex: A stiff knee following surgery forced her to walk with a limp.
example.tran: 手术后她的膝盖活动不便，走路时被迫跛行。

value.tran: 一瘸一拐地走；跛行；蹒跚

value.def: If you say that something such as an organization, process, or vehicle limps along, you mean that it continues slowly or with difficulty, for example because it has been weakened or damaged.

example.ex: In recent years the newspaper had been limping along on limited resources...
example.tran: 近年来这家报社一直在靠有限的资源艰难维持。

example.ex: A British battleship, which had been damaged severely in the battle of Crete, came limping into Pearl Harbor.
example.tran: 一艘在克里特岛战役中严重受损的英国战舰艰难缓慢地驶进珍珠港。

value.def: If you describe something as limp, you mean that it is soft or weak when it should be firm or strong.

example.ex: She was told to reject applicants with limp handshakes...
example.tran: 她被告知要回绝掉那些握手软弱无力的申请者。

example.ex: A residue can build up on the hair shaft, leaving the hair limp and dull looking.
example.tran: 残留物会积聚在头发上，使头发看起来软塌塌的，而且毫无光泽。

example.ex: Flags and bunting hung limply in the still, warm air.
example.tran: 空气暖暖的，也没有风，旗帜和彩旗无精打采地垂着。

value.def: If someone is limp, their body has no strength and is not moving, for example because they are asleep or unconscious.

example.ex: He carried her limp body into the room and laid her on the bed...
example.tran: 他把绵软无力的她抱进房间，放在床上。

example.ex: He hit his head against a rock and went limp.
example.tran: 他的头撞到一块岩石上，身子软了下来。

value.tran: 四肢无力的；身体一动不动的

rootsaffixes.indicate: = threshold 门槛 , 引申为“限制”
rootsaffixes.title: limin, lim

partsOfSpeech.dec: de 加强 + limit 限制 → 定界限
e 出 + limin 门槛，引申为“限制” + ate 做，造成，使… → 消除对事物的限制 → 消除

partsOfSpeech.d: 不稳定；中间状态（原指地狱的边境）

partsOfSpeech.dec: lim 门槛，引申为“限制” + it → 限制
lim 门槛，引申为“限制” + p → 走路受限制的 → 跛行
pre 前 + limin 门槛，引申为“限制” + ary …的 → 入门前的 → 初步的
sub 接近 + lim 门槛，引申为“限制” + ate 做，造成，使… → 接近极限 → 升华
sub 接近 + lim 门槛，引申为“限制” + e → 接近人的极限，升华成神 → 崇高的
sub 下 + limin 门槛，引申为“限制” + al …的 → 被限制在下面的，出于无形意识的 → 潜意识的
